{
  "card_id": "reversal",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Reversal",
  "aliases": [
    "Expansion Met With Expansion",
    "V-Shape Reversal",
    "v-shape reversal",
    "V-Shape Signature",
    "V-Shaped Recovery",
    "V-Shaped Reversal",
    "Vshape",
    "价格反转",
    "反转",
    "趋势反转"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A price phase where directional expansion is immediately met with opposing expansion, forming a higher time frame wick at a relevant high or low. It signals a trend change, distinguished from retracement/consolidation, and is confirmed by a change in state of delivery and swing point formation, invalidating prior protected swings which become liquidity draws.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Price expands into a relevant high or low (e.g., prior day high/low, higher time frame PD array), not an arbitrary intraday level.",
    "The initial expansion is immediately met with aggressive opposing expansion (not a slow retracement or range-bound consolidation), often visible as overlapping fair value gaps or a BPR.",
    "A change in the state of delivery is confirmed: price closes through the series of opposing candles that formed the high/low.",
    "A swing point (protected swing) forms at the reversal level, producing a higher time frame wick.",
    "The reversal is validated by a higher time frame candle closure (e.g., daily or 4-hour) to avoid treating intraday pullbacks as reversals.",
    "Typically, reversal occurs after approximately three expansion candles into the objective, signaling exhaustion.",
    "Invalidation: if the opposing move fails to sustain and price expands back through the swept low/high, the reversal signal is negated.",
    "For V-shape reversal: price sweeps a prior swing high or low (liquidity grab) into a valid point of interest, then immediately and aggressively closes back through the series of opposing candles without consolidation, forming a distinct V-shaped signature.",
    "For V-shape reversal: the reversal must close through the series of opposing candles that created the swept level, confirming a change in state of delivery; closure should be decisive within one to three candles.",
    "For V-shape reversal: if multiple opposing fair value gaps are stacked together, treat them as a single zone and require a clean closure through all."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Reversals mark the end of a directional phase and start of a new one. Traders exit prior trend trades and position in the new direction, entering on lower time frames at the relevant high/low after a change in state of delivery and protected swing formation. The prior protected swing becomes a draw on liquidity. Reversals are expected only at relevant levels aligned with higher time frame bias; after approximately three expansion candles into a key level, avoid new continuation trades and anticipate reversal or consolidation. The concept applies fractally across time frames.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing a retracement (slow, shallow) or consolidation with a reversal, which requires opposing expansion and a change in state of delivery.",
    "Calling a reversal without a confirmed change in state of delivery and swing point formation.",
    "Anticipating a reversal at non-relevant levels (arbitrary intraday) rather than at relevant highs/lows or HTF PD arrays.",
    "Trading a reversal not validated by a higher time frame candle closure, leading to fading a continuation move.",
    "Entering new continuation trades immediately after a large expansion when a reversal or consolidation is more likely.",
    "Failing to invalidate the reversal when price expands back through the swept low/high, or continuing to treat the prior protected swing as safe support/resistance.",
    "Entering before the reversal closes through the opposing candle series (confirms CISD).",
    "Mistaking consolidation, slow closure, or a retracement after the sweep as a valid V-shape reversal.",
    "Entering directly on the initial reversal candle rather than waiting for a continuation entry after the V-shape forms.",
    "Trading the pattern without higher time frame alignment, a point of interest, or confirming tools (SMT, lower timeframe CISD, protected swing).",
    "Flipping bias prematurely based on the sweep alone before the aggressive reversal confirms.",
    "Expecting price to deeply retrace into the body after a clean V-shape; such retracement often invalidates the setup.",
    "Misinterpreting a continuation setup as a new reversal signal once the V-shape has already confirmed the direction.",
    "Failing to treat stacked fair value gaps as a single zone, requiring a clean closure through all.",
    "Trading a V-shape when a higher time frame target has already been reached, risking a phase change.",
    "Entering a V-shape that sweeps a short-term high/low simultaneously, which may be a manipulation."
  ],
